{  
  "response_text": "The data table contains 40 simulation runs, each reporting the initial risk attitudes of 29 households. These runs feature static energy dynamics across all households during timesteps. The energy attitude varies from very risk-averse (𝑟 ≈ -0.11) to strongly risk-seeking (𝑟 ≈ 0.19), largely independent of environmental shocks globally. The mean energy attitude across 29 households is 0.04, with standard error 0.0033. In this extension, the behavioral types of agents are E‐RO-SL1, with knowledge exchanged within 1-unit radius, while social learning probability for attitude modification is made zero. The model features global rainfalls with annual mean 200 and standard deviation 100, shunted into short‐term biomass fluctuations that do not affect energy decisioning by households. The linear trends observed during 100 simulation timesteps suggest that attitude adjustment generally remained unchanged, save for one catchment where it marginally improved following environmental shocks. The initial energy attitude at start‐on‐homepatch? observation was 0.11, directly affecting group dynamics near decision thresholds. The extension model, with risk tolerance at mid‐level (𝑟 = 0.5), operated under predetermined conditions that immunized attitude scaling."
}

